ate course in algebra in order to appreciate cohomological induction and to see its first consequences. Along the way one is able to study homological algebra with a significant application in mind; consequently one sees just what results in that subject are fundamental and what results are minor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHomology theory. 0aLie algebras. 0aLie groups. 7aMATHEMATICS / Algebra / Abstract.2bisacsh  aAlgebra.  aAnalytic group.  aApproximate identity.  aAssociative algebra.  aAssociativity formulas.  aBorel subalgebra.  aBorel-Weil Theorem.  aBoundary operator.  aCartan subgroup.  aChain map.  aChange of rings.  aClosed linear group.  aCohomological induction.  aComplexification.  aConvolution.  aDerivation.  aDerived functor.  aDiffeomorphism.  aDivisible group.  aDual vector space.  aEnough injectives.  aEquivalence.  aEuler-Poincare principle.  aExponential.  aForgetful functor.  aFree resolution.  aFunctor.  aGood category.  aHaar measure.  aHighest weight.  aHomogeneous polynomial.  aHomogeneous tensor.  aI functor.  aInduction, cohomological.  aInner derivation.  aIsotypic subspace.  aK-isotypic subspace.  aLeft exact functor.  aLie algebra.  aLie bracket.  aLinear extension.  aLong exact sequence.  aMackey isomorphism.  aMatrix coefficient.  aMultiplicity.  aNormalized Haar measure.  aPositive root.  aQuotient representation.  aReductive group.  aRegular representation.  aRight exact functor.  aSchur orthogonality.  aSemidirect product.  aSpectral sequence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Mathematical Notes eBook-Package 1970-2016z9783110494921oZDB-23-PMN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1